My thoughts on RH: Gary's comments that it's as if the pandemic never happened in the furniture industry was interesting. He's never framed it like that before. It wasn't a new paradigm in housing or furniture after all. They made money during that period but they are basically back to 2019 trajectory. $RH

RH CC: Lots of unanswered questions you have to consider. Just a week before the bank failure, people thought they'd raise 50 basis points and then Goldman was saying no raise at all. "It's a very uncertain time." $RH

RH CC: Yellen needs to tell people their money is safe. It would create stability in the banking sector. It looks like the shock was temporal. People have returned to their habits. You need something meaningful to change consumers habits. They changed but now are back to normal. But if you think about the yields, and changes in interest rates, it completely flips because of those banks shutting down. $RH

RH CC: In recent history, is spending about 4% on advertising. Used to be 8%. Galleries are dominant presence in markets. Those are expressions of our brand. Brings brand awareness. Requires less advertising. $RH
RH CC: Gary doesn't want to go into details about the layoffs. Says it's not relevant going forward. $RH
RH CC: We've repurchased a billion of our stock at an average of $269. $RH

RH CC: Last quarter I said our core business could be 20% but not with all this investment. Could we generate 20% margins at $3 billion in revenue? Yes. But we're choosing not to. $RH
RH CC: Gary says when he gave 20% guidance last year, that was a COVID collapse but not a COVID collapse AND a housing collapse. $RH

RH CC: Opening galleries for us is a massive investment. We have people there for a month just trying to set and install. We train in the restaurants. Will that normalize once we open up the first few new countries? Yes. Investments won't be so great. $RH

RH CC: Look at what happened to Peloton. It was worth $50 billion and now it's worth $3. Everyone thought that would last forever and Soul Cycle would never open again. In normal times, 20% is the floor. But this is not normal. $RH

RH CC: Is guiding 16% instead of 20%. Our business is tied to housing and refinance markets. It's not rocket science to know this is a really bad time. The fact is, we've been in a massive housing recession for the past year. And COVID comedown. Travel/leisure has opened up. People buying more clothes and jewelry for events. $RH

RH CC: You have to experience the bank collapse to realize it's not normal. If we continue to have runs on banks, the whole thing is a mess. Yellen should tell everyone to calm down. Powell should take the rates to wherever he needs to to kill inflation so we can get back to normal. Zoom in on the 70s. If you think things are crazy now, I can't imagine what that was like to navigate through. $RH

RH CC: If Powell gets this under control, people ought to make him President of the United States. Because in the 1970s, they completely screwed it up. But I'm betting on Powell. Do I think they should have raised a half a point? I do. Does it matter to the banks between 25 or 50? No. Do I wish Yellen would say we will back stop everything? It would take the nervousness out. $RH

RH CC: Pandemic was a "radical change" but it was temporal, not systemic. We don't think this is a lot different from 2009. Were people promotional in 2009? Yes. They are playing that game. You start spending your time pricing from week to week, month to month. You're focused on price, not product. You're playing a completely different game. We've cut through the noise. We're not panicked. $RH

RH CC: There were a lot of things that were really hot with investors for a little while and then they never were again. It's a little boring now. If you want to understand us more, read about Bernard Arnault. It takes a long time to do it. Almost none of the other hard furniture companies are following their strategy. $RH

RH CC: Re-fi's are down like 80%. When they take money out they often use some of it for new furniture. It impacts their business. For our customer, they are smart and savvy investors. Luxury home prices went up more than average. Could we be at 20 if we wanted to (margins). We could. Is that the right thing to do long term? No. Multiple things are hitting us at once. $RH

RH CC: Do we think things are going to get even worse? I have never seen the luxury home market down 45% before. Not even during the financial crisis. Was there erosion during the banking crisis? Yes. It dropped 8 points but it has returned. We haven't factored it into the year. Maybe another 10 point drop if things de-stable further. There's levers we can pull if things slow down. Maybe option to repurchase stock to benefit long term shareholders. $RH

RH CC: Do we think things are going to get even worse? I have never seen the luxury home market down 45% before. Not even during the financial crisis. Was there erosion during the banking crisis? RH CC: "Did you see me sell stock when our stock was $700 a share. No." There's a reason none of sold at $700 a share. We believe it's worth significantly more than that. If we're right, we're going to create extraordinary shareholder value. $RH

RH CC: We're the largest interior residential design business in the US, if not the world. We're creating incredible offices and spaces. Design studios will thread the needle. You'll see the first new concept in London. We're in a good position to play offense. There's no risk here to our balance sheet or model. We may make less money, that's it. I'm not worried where our business is today. We're focused beyond the next 12 months. $RH

RH CC: This is the biggest move in the history of the company. Even more uncertain than 2008-2009. Didn't have inflation or political unrest you have today. Inflation issue will be interesting one. If Fed can navigate with a positive outcome, or any kind of landing. Just land the plane on the other side. Just don't completely crash. A complete crash is the 70s and 80s. We have recessions every 7 to 10 years. Don't be afraid of a recession, I tell people. They last 12 to 18 months. Maybe 24. It's temporal. But 70s and 80s is what we should be scared of. $RH

RH CC: The Outdoor Book, to me, just visually looking at it, feeling the quality, the page, the matte finish. It looks like a new brand but it has the smallest percentage of newness (10 new collections though.) $RH

RH CC: The product that is on its way is the best we've ever done. It's going to be disruptive at the high end and disruptive to those below us. We have the scale to buy and stock inventory. Wayfair and others can't really buy in volume. They can't drive efficiencies. Wayfair made money at the peak of the pandemic. Will Wayfair be able to cut prices and make it? I don't know. We have a really great model in our industry. $RH

RH CC: Let's see what happens when all those people have to anniversary their promotions. Let's see what happens when their operating margins have to grind down to where they were historically. We guided to a mid-point of 16. We entered the pandemic with 14.3%. We're ahead of where we were. I don't know if everyone else is going to end up there. RH CC: We're not "pushing the panic button of promotions." We're not trying to hold onto the illusions that business is where it was during the pandemic. We're acting like it never happened. Does it matter if our business looks like 2019 coming out of it? $RH
